 </m:semantics>
</m:math>

</equation><para id="id208010">Based on the above definition, one observes <m:math overflow="scroll"><m:mi>φ</m:mi></m:math> has to be a constant if
<m:math overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mi>α</m:mi><m:mo>&gt;</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:math>. Hence, this is not very useful for determining regularity of
order <m:math overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mi>α</m:mi><m:mo>&gt;</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:math>. However, using the above definition, Hölder
regularity of any order <m:math overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mi>r</m:mi><m:mo>&gt;</m:mo><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:mrow></m:math> is defined as follows:</para>
      <para id="id208070"><emphasis effect="bold">Definition 2 (Hölder regularity)</emphasis> <emphasis effect="italics">
A function 
